<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="bilayer_lbd"><title>tutor</title><page id="ba5ae107557b4c28b90455549c4ed86a"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="q1"><body><p id="ad3046911cba347bfba886972e63852c9">What do you think would happen to the rate of lateral phospholipid movement if the concentration of unsaturated fatty acids increased?</p></body><multiple_choice id="acba5274cb5941efbfc082543660c4a3" labels="false" select="single" shuffle="true"><choice value="A">The rate would decrease</choice><choice value="B">There would be no change</choice><choice value="C">The rate would increase</choice></multiple_choice><part id="i7d4a7c557039461fb5bc986f63736135"><skillref idref="levels_cell_membrane_fluid_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa7fb987eaa364880b09c73d813dbe886">Incorrect. Increasing the amount of unsaturated fatty acids would make a membrane more fluid.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="af4989a3da2ae446188f293a9aed3f9a1">Incorrect. Unsaturated fatty acids increase fluidity while saturated fatty acids make it less fluid.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="ae2eb56e85f534040b2c3b430798c4b0c">Correct. In some species, altering the ratio of unsaturated to saturated fatty acids is an important mechanism in maintaining fluidity.</p></feedback></response></part></question></page></assessment>
